  "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
  "body": "When creating a service passing the annotation `service.beta.kubernetes.io/openstack-internal-load-balancer: \"false\"`, two IPs are created in the service, a private and a public:\r\n```\r\nLoadBalancer Ingress:\t10.11.4.90, 150.165.x.y\r\n```\r\n\r\nHaving a private IP is not a desired scenario for service discovery in federated global environments.   If we have, for example, a cluster in GKE and join a local OpenStack cluster, this private IP is written in the DNS zone but the GKE cluster won't be able to access it. \r\n\r\nWe could add an annotation to say we don't want the private IP to be registered in service's LoadBalancer Ingress field, like:\r\n\r\n`loadbalancer.openstack.org/register-internal-ip=false` or\r\n`service.beta.kubernetes.io/register-internal-ip=false` \r\n\r\nAnd when it's false, only the public IP would be written in the service, therefore in the DNS zone\r\n\r\n/kind feature\r\n\r\n",
